exhaustive treatment of the subject in the second chapter of his disserta- tion, thought that in the Y class iste had been deleted ‘ ubi nudum, ubi ante suurn nomen, ubi post primurn adiectivum, si substantivo apponuntur duo adiectiva‚ positum erat'3 but Scheuer rightly doubts how a copyist could have arrived at such a ‘ law,' and quotes against it the instances at 23. 73 41. 20 3 26. 6 (where there is a general agreement for iste in the MSS.).

It seems certain that AB cannot be invariably right, while on the other hand the Y class cannot be followed in all cases.
